@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Ontological Risk Management";
    Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_CustomLayoutWithLogin.cshtml";
}
<style>
    body,
    html {
        height: 100%;
        margin: 0;
        display: flex;
        flex-direction: column;
        justify-content: space-between;
    }

    .main-content {
        flex: 1;
        display: flex;
        justify-content: center;
        align-items: center;
        margin-top: 60px;
        /* Adjust this value to increase space from the navbar */
        margin-bottom: 60px;
        /* Adjust this value to increase space from the footer */
    }

    .info-box {
        background-color: #333;
        padding: 40px;
        max-width: 800px;
        text-align: left;
        border-radius: 10px;
        color: #fff;
    }

    .info-box h2 {
        margin-bottom: 20px;
    }

    .info-box p {
        margin-bottom: 15px;
        line-height: 1.6;
    }

    .btn-primary {
        display: inline-block;
        padding: 10px 20px;
        background-color: #007bff;
        color: #fff;
        border: none;
        border-radius: 5px;
        text-decoration: none;
    }

    .btn-primary:hover {
        background-color: #0056b3;
        color: #fff;
    }

    /* Footer styles */
    .footer-section {
        background-color: #111;
        color: white;
        text-align: center;
        padding: 20px 0;
        width: 100%;
    }

    .footer-section p {
        margin: 5px 0;
    }
</style>

<div class="main-content">
    <div class="info-box">
        <h2>Understanding Ontology in the Scope of Risk Management</h2>
        <p>
            Think of an ontology as a shared language for risk. It's a structured framework that defines the key
            players,
            relationships, and ideas involved in tackling risks. No more confusion over terms – everyone's on the same
            page.
        </p>
        <p>
            Building a comprehensive ontology supercharges your risk assessment. It streamlines the process, boosts
            communication, and ensures you're not missing any hidden threats. This means defining all the risk types,
            what
            causes them, how bad they could get, and how different factors interact.
        </p>
        <p>
            But ontologies don't stop there. They're the glue that connects your risk management across departments and
            systems. Imagine risk tools and methods that all speak the same language – that's the power of ontologies!
        </p>
        <p>
            In a nutshell, an ontological approach to risk management brings clarity and structure, making your whole
            process more effective and efficient. It's like giving your risk management a major upgrade!
        </p>
        <a class="btn btn-primary" asp-controller="Home" asp-action="Demo">Go To Demo</a>
    </div>
</div>

